{"title_page": "Ubacisi", "text_new": "{{Short description|Genus of spiders}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| taxon = Ubacisi capensis\n| authority = (Griswold, 1987)\n| parent_authority = Griswold, 2001<ref name=NMBE />\n}}\n\n'''''Ubacisi''''' is a [[monotypic taxon|monotypic]] [[genus]] of [[Africa]]n [[Araneomorphae|araneomorph]] spiders in the family [[Cyatholipidae]] containing the single species, '''''Ubacisi capensis'''''. It was first described by C. E. Griswold in 2001,<ref name=Gris2001>{{cite journal| last=Griswold| first=C. E.| year=2001| title=A monograph of the living world genera and Afrotropical species of cyatholipid spiders (Araneae, Orbiculariae, Araneoidea, Cyatholipidae).| journal=Memoirs of the California Academy of Sciences| pages=1\u2013251| volume=26}}</ref> and has only been found in [[South Africa]].<ref name=NMBE>{{cite web| title=Gen. Ubacisi Griswold, 2001| website=World Spider Catalog Version 20.0| accessdate=2019-05-30| year=2019| publisher=Natural History Museum Bern| url=http://www.wsc.nmbe.ch/genus/674| doi=10.24436/2}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q18093762|from2=Q1851362}}\n\n[[Category:Cyatholipidae]]\n[[Category:Monotypic Araneomorphae genera]]\n[[Category:Spiders described in 1987]]\n[[Category:Spiders of South Africa]]\n\n\n{{Araneomorphae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Genus of spiders}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| taxon = Ubacisi capensis\n| authority = (Griswold, 1987)\n| parent_authority = Griswold, 2001<ref name=NMBE />\n}}\n\n'''''Ubacisi''''' is a [[monotypic taxon|monotypic]] [[genus]] of [[Africa]]n [[Araneomorphae|araneomorph]] spiders in the [[Cyatholipidae]] family containing the single species, '''''Ubacisi capensis'''''. It was first described by C. E. Griswold in 2001,<ref name=Gris2001>{{cite journal| last=Griswold| first=C. E.| year=2001| title=A monograph of the living world genera and Afrotropical species of cyatholipid spiders (Araneae, Orbiculariae, Araneoidea, Cyatholipidae).| journal=Memoirs of the California Academy of Sciences| pages=1\u2013251| volume=26}}</ref> and has only been found in [[South Africa]].<ref name=NMBE>{{cite web| title=Gen. Ubacisi Griswold, 2001| website=World Spider Catalog Version 20.0| accessdate=2019-05-30| year=2019| publisher=Natural History Museum Bern| url=http://www.wsc.nmbe.ch/genus/674| doi=10.24436/2}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q18093762|from2=Q1851362}}\n\n[[Category:Cyatholipidae]]\n[[Category:Monotypic Araneomorphae genera]]\n[[Category:Spiders described in 1987]]\n[[Category:Spiders of South Africa]]\n\n\n{{Araneomorphae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ubacisi"}
{"title_page": "Palm Trees and Power Lines", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Palm Trees and Power Lines\n| type       = Album\n| artist     = [[Sugarcult]]\n| cover      = Palmtreesandpowerlines.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = April 13, 2004\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Full Kilt Studio, Third Stone Recordings, Hollywood, California\n| genre      = [[Alternative rock]], [[pop punk]]\n| length     = 40:43\n| label      = [[Fearless Records|Fearless]], [[Artemis Records|Artemis]]\n| producer   = Gavin MacKillop\n| prev_title = [[Start Static]]\n| prev_year  = 2001\n| next_title = [[Lights Out (Sugarcult album)|Lights Out]]\n| next_year  = 2006\n| misc       = {{Singles\n| type       = studio\n| single1    = [[Memory (Sugarcult song)|Memory]]\n| single2    = She's the Blade\n| single1date = March 16, 2004\n| single2date = August 31, 2004\n}}\n}}\n'''Palm Trees and Power Lines''' is the fourth studio album by American rock band [[Sugarcult]].  The album contains the [[MTV]] hits \"Memory\" and \"She's the Blade\".<ref>SPIN - Oct 2006 - Page 104 Vol. 22, No. 10 \"Sugarcult. Lights Out *\u2022* FEARLESS/V2 Raging riffs for getting drunk and getting lucky Though these SoCal pop punks sneaked onto MTV with their 2004 single \"Memory,\" the hard-partying reputation they earned after the song's success was ...\"</ref> This is the band\u2019s first album to feature Kenny Livingston on drums. \n\n==Production==\nRecording took place at Full Kilt Studio and Third Stone Recording in North Hollywood, California with producer Gavin MacKillop. Additional production was done by Tim Pagnotta. Wes Sideman acted as assistant engineer at Third Stone Recording. John Nooney, Mauro Rubbi and Trent Slatton engineered the [[Pro-Tools]] sessions. Tim Cullen provided additional backing vocals. [[Alain Johannes]] performed additional guitar. Nooney and [[Ariel Rechtshaid]] contributed keyboards. Slatton provided programming. [[Tom Lord-Alge]] mixed \"She's the Blade\", \"Crying\", \"[[Memory (Sugarcult song)|Memory]]\", \"Back to California\" and \"Over\" at South Beach Studio. [[Mark Trombino]] mixed \"Worst December\" and \"Champagne\" at Chalice Recording Studios with assistance from Alan Mason. Mackillop mixed \"Destination Anywhere\", \"What You Say\", \"Head Up\" and \"Counting Stars\". [[Evan Frankfort]] mixed \"Sign Off\". [[Brian Gardner]] mastered the recordings at Bernie Grudman Mastering in Hollywood, California.<ref name=PTAPLbooklet/> \n\n==Release==\nOn December 15, 2003, ''Palm Trees and Power Lines'' was announced for release.<ref name=AAannounce>{{cite web|url=http://www.alternativeaddiction.com/AANewsArticle/sugarcult-to-release-new-album-in-march|title=Sugarcult to Release New Album in March|work=Alternative Addiction|date=December 13, 2003|accessdate=April 27, 2017}}</ref> In January 2004, the band went on a Japanese tour with [[Good Charlotte]]. During the same month, the band filmed amusic video for \"Memory\".<ref name=MelodicJanuary>{{cite web|url=http://melodic.net/?page=news&id=2036|title=Sugarcult update.|work=Melodic|author=Wippsson, Johan |date=January 24, 2004|accessdate=April 27, 2017}}</ref> \"Memory\" was released to radio on March 16.<ref name=FMQB>{{cite web|url=http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=16771|title=FMQB Airplay Archive: Modern Rock|publisher=Friday Morning Quarterback Album Report, Incorporated|accessdate=October 30, 2016}}</ref> On February 25, the album's track listing was revealed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://melodic.net/?page=news&id=2176|title=Listen to a new track from Sugarcult's upcoming album|work=Melodic|author=Wippsson, Johan |date=February 25, 2004|accessdate=April 27, 2017}}</ref> After being originally scheduled for release on March 9,<ref name=AAannounce/> the album was eventually released on April 13.<ref name=MelodicJanuary/> The album is named after the scenery in California where the band members live, as the skyline is littered with palm trees and power lines.<ref name=\"bvm\">{{cite web  | last = Black Velvet  | first = Shari  | title = All Roads Lead To Sugarcult  | url=http://www.blackvelvetmagazine.com/sugarcult.htm  | accessdate = 2007-05-14 }}</ref> On the album cover, a few pieces of Californian scenery can be seen in the background, such as a liquor store, which Pagnotta visits in the documentary ''Back to the Disaster''. \"She's the Blade\" was released to radio on August 31.<ref name=FMQB/> In October and November, the group supported [[Green Day]] on their headlining US tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1490903/new-found-glory-to-shoot-top-secret-video-before-green-day-tour/|title=New Found Glory To Shoot 'Top Secret' Video Before Green Day Tour|work=MTV|publisher=Viacom|author=Montgomery, James|date=September 10, 2004|accessdate=July 21, 2018}}</ref> In February 2005, the group supported [[Hawthorne Heights]] on the [[Take Action Tour]] across the US.<ref>Sharpe-Young 2005, p. 168</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r681089|pure_url=yes}} Allmusic review]</ref>\n|rev2 = ''[[The Daily Californian]]''\n|rev2score = Favorable <ref>http://archive.dailycal.org/article.php?id=14960</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[Drowned in Sound]]''\n|rev3score = 6/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/3658/reviews/9458-|title=Album Review: Sugarcult - Palm Trees and Power Lines|publisher=}}</ref>\n|rev4 = [[musicOMH]]\n|rev4score = Favorable <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicomh.com/reviews/albums/sugarcult-palm-trees-and-power-lines|title=Sugarcult \u2013 Palm Trees And Power Lines - Album Reviews - musicOMH|publisher=}}</ref>\n|rev5 = ''[[Melodic (magazine)|Melodic]]''\n|rev5score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://melodic.net/?page=review&id=2058|title=Sugarcult - Palm Trees And Power Lines|work=Melodic|author=Ellis, Andrew|date=March 16, 2004|accessdate=April 27, 2017}}</ref>\n|rev6 = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n|rev6score = Favorable <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/sugarcult-palmtrees/|title=Sugarcult: Palm Trees and Power Lines|publisher=}}</ref>\n|rev7 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n|rev7score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/5265790/palm_trees_and_power_lines |title=Rolling Stone review |work=Rolling Stone |accessdate=13 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071002091458/http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/5265790/palm_trees_and_power_lines |archivedate=October 2, 2007 }}</ref>\n|rev8 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n|rev8score = C-<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Is53I1fXC1YC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA108#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=SPIN|first=SPIN Media|last=LLC|date=11 December 2016|publisher=SPIN Media LLC|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n}}<!-- Automatically generated by DASHBot-->\n''Palm Trees and Power Lines'' sold 22,000 copies, reaching number 46 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.absolutepunk.net:80/|archiveurl=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20141201082639/http://www.absolutepunk.net/|title=AbsolutePunk.net|work=AbsolutePunk|publisher=SpinMedia|archivedate=December 1, 2014|accessdate=August 2, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The album received mixed to favorable reviews from critics. Johnny Loftus of [[Allmusic]] gives a favorable review,  concluding that \"Sugarcult are thankfully more concerned with pleasing the crowd than making a statement.\" Punktastic characterizes the album as \"one hell of a grower,\" a record \"that shows maturity without ever coming across as trite or predictable.\"  The review goes on to call the album \"a fine record which, while not as anthemic and instant as its predecessor, is destined to be a sure-fire summer hit.\"\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs by Tim Pagnotta, all music by Pagnotta and Sugarcult.<ref name=PTAPLbooklet/>\n\n# \"She's the Blade\" \u2013 2:59\n# \"Crying\" \u2013 3:29\n# \"[[Memory (Sugarcult song)|Memory]]\" \u2013 3:46\n# \"Worst December\" \u2013 3:37\n# \"Back to California\" \u2013 4:07\n# \"Destination Anywhere\" \u2013 3:51\n# \"Champagne\" \u2013 2:56\n# \"What You Say\" \u2013 2:39\n# \"Over\" \u2013 3:24\n# \"Head Up\" \u2013 3:56\n# \"Counting Stars\" \u2013 3:38\n# \"Sign Off\" \u2013 2:13\n# \"Blackout\" (Japanese bonus track) \u2013 3:10\n\n'''Note'''\n* An acoustic version of \"Memory\" was released on the compilation album ''[[Punk Goes Acoustic]]''.\n\n==Personnel==\nPersonnel per booklet.<ref name=PTAPLbooklet>{{cite AV media notes|title=Palm Trees and Power Lines |others=[[Sugarcult]] |year=2004|type=Booklet|publisher=[[Fearless Records|Fearless]]/[[Artemis Records|Artemis]]|id=RCD17018}}</ref>\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Sugarcult\n* [[Tim Pagnotta]] \u2013 lead vocals, rhythm guitar\n* [[Marko DeSantis|Marko 72]] \u2013 lead guitar\n* [[Airin Older]] \u2013 bass, backing vocals\n* Kenny Livingston \u2013 drums\n\n;Additional musicians\n* Tim Cullen \u2013 additional backing vocals\n* [[Alain Johannes]] \u2013 additional guitar\n* John Nooney \u2013 keyboards\n* [[Ariel Rechtshaid]] \u2013 keyboards\n* Trent Slatton \u2013 programming\n{{col-2}}\n;Production\n* Gavin Mackillop \u2013 producer, recording; mixing <small>(tracks 6, 8, 10 and 11)</small>\n* Nick Condodina \u2013 [[enhanced CD]] footage\n* Sim Klugerman \u2013 enhanced CD footage\n* Sugarcult \u2013 enhanced CD footage\n* John Logsdon \u2013 enhanced CD editing\n* Piper Ferguson \u2013 band photos\n* Lisa Johnson \u2013 band photos\n* Yoshika Horita \u2013 band photos\n* Gregg Kulick \u2013 art direction, design\n* [[Tom Lord-Alge]] \u2013 mixing <small>(tracks 1\u20133, 5 and 9)</small>\n* [[Mark Trombino]] \u2013 mixing <small>(tracks 4 and 7)</small>\n* Alan Manson \u2013 mixing assistant\n* [[Evan Frankfort]] \u2013 mixing <small>(track 12)</small>\n* [[Brian Gardner]] \u2013 mastering\n* Wes Sideman \u2013 assistant engineer\n* John Nooney \u2013 [[Pro-Tools]] engineer\n* Mauro Rubbi \u2013 Pro-Tools engineer, drum tech\n* Trent Slatton \u2013 Pro-Tools engineer\n* Tim Pagnotta \u2013 additional production\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n'''Sources'''\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Sharpe-Young|first=Garry|title=New Wave of American Heavy Metal|year=2005|publisher=Zonda Books|location=New Plymouth, NZ|isbn=9780958268400|edition=1st}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.sugarcult.com Official website]\n{{Sugarcult}}\n[[Category:Sugarcult albums]]\n[[Category:2004 albums]]\n[[Category:Fearless Records albums]]\n[[Category:Artemis Records albums]]\n\n[[de:Sugarcult]]\n[[pl:Sugarcult]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Palm Trees and Power Lines\n| type       = Album\n| artist     = [[Sugarcult]]\n| cover      = Palmtreesandpowerlines.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = April 13, 2004\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Full Kilt Studio, Third Stone Recordings, Hollywood, California\n| genre      = [[Alternative rock]], [[pop punk]]\n| length     = 40:43\n| label      = [[Fearless Records|Fearless]], [[Artemis Records|Artemis]]\n| producer   = Gavin MacKillop\n| prev_title = [[Start Static]]\n| prev_year  = 2001\n| next_title = [[Lights Out (Sugarcult album)|Lights Out]]\n| next_year  = 2006\n| misc       = {{Singles\n| type       = studio\n| single1    = [[Memory (Sugarcult song)|Memory]]\n| single2    = She's the Blade\n| single1date = March 16, 2004\n| single2date = August 31, 2004\n}}\n}}\n'''Palm Trees and Power Lines''' is the fourth studio album by American rock band [[Sugarcult]].  The album contains the [[MTV]] hits \"Memory\" and \"She's the Blade\".<ref>SPIN - Oct 2006 - Page 104 Vol. 22, No. 10 \"Sugarcult. Lights Out *\u2022* FEARLESS/V2 Raging riffs for getting drunk and getting lucky Though these SoCal pop punks sneaked onto MTV with their 2004 single \"Memory,\" the hard-partying reputation they earned after the song's success was ...\"</ref> This is the band\u2019s first album to feature Kenny Livingston on drums. \n\n==Production==\nRecording took place at Full Kilt Studio and Third Stone Recording in North Hollywood, California with producer Gavin MacKillop. Additional production was done by Tim Pagnotta. Wes Sideman acted as assistant engineer at Third Stone Recording. John Nooney, Mauro Rubbi and Trent Slatton engineered the [[Pro-Tools]] sessions. Tim Cullen provided additional backing vocals. [[Alain Johannes]] performed additional guitar. Nooney and [[Ariel Rechtshaid]] contributed keyboards. Slatton provided programming. [[Tom Lord-Alge]] mixed \"She's the Blade\", \"Crying\", \"[[Memory (Sugarcult song)|Memory]]\", \"Back to California\" and \"Over\" at South Beach Studio. [[Mark Trombino]] mixed \"Worst December\" and \"Champagne\" at Chalice Recording Studios with assistance from Alan Mason. Mackillop mixed \"Destination Anywhere\", \"What You Say\", \"Head Up\" and \"Counting Stars\". [[Evan Frankfort]] mixed \"Sign Off\". [[Brian Gardner]] mastered the recordings at Bernie Grudman Mastering in Hollywood, California.<ref name=PTAPLbooklet/> \n\n==Release==\nOn December 15, 2003, ''Palm Trees and Power Lines'' was announced for release.<ref name=AAannounce>{{cite web|url=http://www.alternativeaddiction.com/AANewsArticle/sugarcult-to-release-new-album-in-march|title=Sugarcult to Release New Album in March|work=Alternative Addiction|date=December 13, 2003|accessdate=April 27, 2017}}</ref> In January 2004, the band went on a Japanese tour with [[Good Charlotte]]. During the same month, the band filmed amusic video for \"Memory\".<ref name=MelodicJanuary>{{cite web|url=http://melodic.net/?page=news&id=2036|title=Sugarcult update.|work=Melodic|author=Wippsson, Johan |date=January 24, 2004|accessdate=April 27, 2017}}</ref> \"Memory\" was released to radio on March 16.<ref name=FMQB>{{cite web|url=http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=16771|title=FMQB Airplay Archive: Modern Rock|publisher=Friday Morning Quarterback Album Report, Incorporated|accessdate=October 30, 2016}}</ref> On February 25, the album's track listing was revealed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://melodic.net/?page=news&id=2176|title=Listen to a new track from Sugarcult's upcoming album|work=Melodic|author=Wippsson, Johan |date=February 25, 2004|accessdate=April 27, 2017}}</ref> After being originally scheduled for release on March 9,<ref name=AAannounce/> the album was eventually released on April 13.<ref name=MelodicJanuary/> The album is named after the scenery in California where the band members live, as the skyline is littered with palm trees and power lines.<ref name=\"bvm\">{{cite web  | last = Black Velvet  | first = Shari  | title = All Roads Lead To Sugarcult  | url=http://www.blackvelvetmagazine.com/sugarcult.htm  | accessdate = 2007-05-14 }}</ref> On the album cover, a few pieces of Californian scenery can be seen in the background, such as a liquor store, which Pagnotta visits in the documentary ''Back to the Disaster''. \"She's the Blade\" was released to radio on August 31.<ref name=FMQB/> In October and November, the group supported [[Green Day]] on their headlining US tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1490903/new-found-glory-to-shoot-top-secret-video-before-green-day-tour/|title=New Found Glory To Shoot 'Top Secret' Video Before Green Day Tour|work=MTV|publisher=Viacom|author=Montgomery, James|date=September 10, 2004|accessdate=July 21, 2018}}</ref> In February 2005, the group supported [[Hawthorne Heights]] on the [[Take Action Tour]] across the US.<ref>Sharpe-Young 2005, p. 168</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r681089|pure_url=yes}} Allmusic review]</ref>\n|rev2 = ''[[The Daily Californian]]''\n|rev2score = Favorable <ref>http://archive.dailycal.org/article.php?id=14960</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[Drowned in Sound]]''\n|rev3score = 6/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/3658/reviews/9458-|title=Album Review: Sugarcult - Palm Trees and Power Lines|publisher=}}</ref>\n|rev4 = [[musicOMH]]\n|rev4score = Favorable <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicomh.com/reviews/albums/sugarcult-palm-trees-and-power-lines|title=Sugarcult \u2013 Palm Trees And Power Lines - Album Reviews - musicOMH|publisher=}}</ref>\n|rev5 = ''[[Melodic (magazine)|Melodic]]''\n|rev5score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://melodic.net/?page=review&id=2058|title=Sugarcult - Palm Trees And Power Lines|work=Melodic|author=Ellis, Andrew|date=March 16, 2004|accessdate=April 27, 2017}}</ref>\n|rev6 = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n|rev6score = Favorable <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/sugarcult-palmtrees/|title=Sugarcult: Palm Trees and Power Lines|publisher=}}</ref>\n|rev7 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n|rev7score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/5265790/palm_trees_and_power_lines |title=Rolling Stone review |work=Rolling Stone |accessdate=13 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071002091458/http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/5265790/palm_trees_and_power_lines |archivedate=October 2, 2007 }}</ref>\n|rev8 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n|rev8score = C-<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Is53I1fXC1YC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA108#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=SPIN|first=SPIN Media|last=LLC|date=11 December 2016|publisher=SPIN Media LLC|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n}}<!-- Automatically generated by DASHBot-->\n''Palm Trees and Power Lines'' sold 22,000 copies, reaching number 46 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.absolutepunk.net:80/|archiveurl=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20141201082639/http://www.absolutepunk.net/|title=AbsolutePunk.net|work=AbsolutePunk|publisher=SpinMedia|archivedate=December 1, 2014|accessdate=August 2, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The album received mixed to favorable reviews from critics. Johnny Loftus of [[Allmusic]] gives a favorable review,  concluding that \"Sugarcult are thankfully more concerned with pleasing the crowd than making a statement.\" Punktastic characterizes the album as \"one hell of a grower,\" a record \"that shows maturity without ever coming across as trite or predictable.\"  The review goes on to call the album \"a fine record which, while not as anthemic and instant as its predecessor, is destined to be a sure-fire summer hit.\"\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs by Tim Pagnotta, all music by Pagnotta and Sugarcult.<ref name=PTAPLbooklet/>\n\n# \"She's the Blade\" \u2013 2:59\n# \"Crying\" \u2013 3:29\n# \"[[Memory (Sugarcult song)|Memory]]\" \u2013 3:46\n# \"Worst December\" \u2013 3:37\n# \"Back to California\" \u2013 4:07\n# \"Destination Anywhere\" \u2013 3:51\n# \"Champagne\" \u2013 2:56\n# \"What You Say\" \u2013 2:39\n# \"Over\" \u2013 3:24\n# \"Head Up\" \u2013 3:56\n# \"Counting Stars\" \u2013 3:38\n# \"Sign Off\" \u2013 2:13\n# \"Blackout\" (Japanese bonus track) \u2013 3:10\n\n'''Note'''\n* An acoustic version of \"Memory\" was released on the compilation album ''[[Punk Goes Acoustic]]''.\n\n==Personnel==\nPersonnel per booklet.<ref name=PTAPLbooklet>{{cite AV media notes|title=Palm Trees and Power Lines |others=[[Sugarcult]] |year=2004|type=Booklet|publisher=[[Fearless Records|Fearless]]/[[Artemis Records|Artemis]]|id=RCD17018}}</ref>\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Sugarcult\n* [[Tim Pagnotta]] \u2013 vocals, guitar\n* [[Marko DeSantis|Marko 72]] \u2013 guitar\n* [[Airin Older]] \u2013 bass, vocals\n* Kenny Livingston \u2013 drums\n\n;Additional musicians\n* Tim Cullen \u2013 additional backing vocals\n* [[Alain Johannes]] \u2013 additional guitar\n* John Nooney \u2013 keyboards\n* [[Ariel Rechtshaid]] \u2013 keyboards\n* Trent Slatton \u2013 programming\n{{col-2}}\n;Production\n* Gavin Mackillop \u2013 producer, recording; mixing <small>(tracks 6, 8, 10 and 11)</small>\n* Nick Condodina \u2013 [[enhanced CD]] footage\n* Sim